node.text:
To celebrate @elijahcraig Old-Fashioned Week, Lynnette Marrero (@drinksat6), bar director of Llama San (@llamasannyc), Llama Inn (@llamainnnyc) and Wonderbar (@wonderbarbeacon), shares how to make her Three Bites of the Apple, an Old-Fashioned inspired by autumn in the Hudson Valley. ⁠
Get the recipe at punchdrink.com and learn more about how you can raise an Elijah Craig Bourbon Old-Fashioned to support the bar community at OldFashionedWeek.com.
#punchpartner @elijahcraig #oldfashionedweek @rwcfusa 
#oldfashioned #cocktail #bartender

Welcome to a special charity episode of “Tip Your Bartender” all about Aperitivo to benefit @rwcfusa! This episode supports industry workers in need by raising funds for @rwcfusa. You can make a contribution by going to the link in our profile, or heading over to @rwcfusa. To date, the Bacardi family of brands has contributed over $150,000 to aid in @rwcfusa’s ongoing relief efforts. @martinirossius will continue their support with a donation following this segment. #raiseyourspirits #drinkpunchtyb

node.text: In a literal interpretation of Don the Beachcomber’s dictum “What one rum can’t do, three rums can,” @samson_miller’s Three Mile Island, a smoked rum Old-Fashioned variation, blends three Barbados rums as the base. “What I love about this is we’re not actually using any wood to smoke the cocktail,” explains our Bartender in Residence, who opts instead to char dried orange peels, drawing out citrusy notes in the rum base. Check out the recipe via the link in our profile. #bartenderinresidence #drinkpunch 📷: @kellypuleio

node.text: You might not think to pair St-Germain with Cynar, luckily @jroertel did. The two ingredients play surprisingly well together alongside Jamaican rum in this quasi-tropical drink. The warm funk of Smith & Cross creates a heavy base for the bittersweet co-mingling of amaro and elderflower. Get the recipe for the Artichoke Hold via the link in our profile. #drinkpunch 📷: @lizzieamunro

node.text:
When @maisonpremiere opened in 2011, the debut menu included a classic Pimm’s Cup, consisting of the gin-based herbal liqueur Pimm’s No. 1 dressed up with cucumber, housemade ginger syrup and a bouquet of fresh mint. Ten years later, the Pimm’s Cup is still on the menu. But, to date, the recipe has changed 37 times—a testament to just how versatile the drink can be. "Of course, we cocktail-bar it to death,” says bar director @youngwilliamelliot. 

Pictured above is the Summer 2021 version created by head bartender @st.rhea, which leans into the flavor profile of the Pimm’s liqueur, enhancing it with orange, lemon and ginger syrup, and shaking the drink with cucumber in the tin, a riff on the regal shake. Swipe right to see the Fall 2019 version (French plum brandy, housemade blueberry-cardamom cordial, Amontillado sherry, cranberry bitters) and the Winter 2017 edition (overproof bourbon, crème de menthe, crème de peche, PX sherry)—and head to the link in our profile for more on the cocktail that's always under construction at Maison Premiere. #drinkpunch 📷: @lizzieamunro

node.text: The Samson Swizzle is @samson_miller’s tropical ode to the Queen's Park Swizzle. In the tiki-inflected take, he splits the base between Jamaican and Barbadian rum and gives it “a tropical vibe” simply by swapping traditional simple syrup with a spiced passionfruit syrup. “It’s a pretty simple switch, but it gave the drink a whole new depth,” explains Miller, a member of our Bartender in Residence Class of 2021. Head to the link in our profile for the recipe. #bartenderinresidence #drinkpunch 📷: @kellypuleio

node.text: This is what happens when you throw a Pornstar Martini in the blender. In her frosty take, @dramawise opts for botanical-forward gin instead of the usual vodka. She notes that the addition of Chinola and Licor 43 keep it “nice and boozy”, while an added measure of passion fruit puree and pitted umeboshi (salted Japanese plum) keep the blended drink creamy with an unexpected layer of umami. Get the recipe for Sex Work Is Real Work via the link in our profile. #drinkpunch 📷: @lizzieamunro

node.text: The Cadillac Margarita, a combination of high-end tequila with Grand Marnier subbed in for triple sec, introduced the idea of "luxury" to the humble Margarita. As with many cocktails of the era, the drink’s true origin story is a murky matter of debate, but the glorified cocktail created a template for the kinds of lavish Margaritas that remain standards at chain restaurants today. Head to the link in our profile for @aarongoldfarb's investigation into the origins of the Margarita's opulent cousin. #drinkpunch 📷: @lizzieamunro ⁠

node.text: @tarbyparty has unlocked the secret to the fluffiest Ramos Gin Fizz ever. The @deathandcompany co-owner uses an iSi nitrous oxide (N2O) cream whipper, a kitchen gadget typically used to produce and dispense soft cheeses or whipped cream, to create this "light-as-air" rendition. But the RGF is far from the only drink that benefits from a whipped cream dispenser. The nitrous oxide technique works for any recipe that calls for a protein component, such as egg whites, cream or aquafaba—think traditional sours, flips and even eggnog. Head to the link in our profile—and swipe right—to see how it's done. #drinkpunch 📷: @dylanandjeni

node.text: Angostura takes center stage in this spicy riff on the Piña Colada. Based on the structure of a traditional Piña Colada (rum, pineapple and coconut), @zacoverman replaces most of the rum with Angostura bitters. A bit of lime and overproof rum smooth out and balance the lip-curling bitters, while pineapple and cream of coconut maintain the Piña’s tropical spirit.
